    <text>
        <body>
           <div type="edition" subtype="primary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="01"/><w n="5">Σαράπιδι</w> <w n="10">Ἴσιδι</w> <w n="15">Νείλωι</w>
                    <lb n="02"/><w lemma="καί" rend="καὶ" n="20">καὶ</w> <w lemma="βασιλεύς" rend="βασιλεῖ" n="25">βασιλεῖ</w> <w n="30">Πτολεμαίωι</w>
                    <lb n="03"/><w lemma="καί" rend="καὶ" n="35">καὶ</w> <w lemma="βασίλισσα" rend="βασιλίσσηι" n="40">βασιλίσσηι</w> <w n="45">Βερενίκηι</w>
                    <lb n="04"/><w lemma="θεός" rend="θεοῖς" n="50">θεοῖς</w> <w lemma="εὐεργέτης" rend="Εὐεργέταις" n="55">Εὐεργέταις</w>
                    <lb n="05"/><w n="60">Καλλικράτης</w> <w n="65">Ἀντιπάτρου.</w>
                </ab>
          </div>
            <div type="apparatus"><!-- references in note will go in @source on app once bibliography is encoded -->
                <listApp>
                    <app loc="5">
                        <rdg>Καλλικράτης  <note>corr. from</note> Καλλικράτηι <note>by the stonecutter</note></rdg>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div> 
            <div type="translation">
                <p>To Sarapis, Isis and Neilos, and to King Ptolemy and Queen Berenike, gods Euergetai, Kallikrates son of Antipatros.</p>
            </div> 
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>One of three such dedications (see also 094 and 095)<!-- link to inscriptions -->, of which only two include Neilos. The provenance of 93 is unrecorded but since the content makes it very probable that it also comes from Kanopos it is included here. The dedicant Kallikrates is Trismegistos P245120<!-- link to TM people -->.</p>
            </div>
